<font color="#FF0000">TO DOC DEL</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan 18  4:14:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
  To Doc Del                                                  <br>
   The bravest man I ever knew was a medic.<br>
 We were in a recon platoon in the central highlands in 1970. After losing about a third of our platoon at the onset of an enemy offensive in the Hep Duc Valley. We were reenforced with a line company. The next night we were attacked by the N.V.A.. We lost our platoon leader, the company comander of the line company, thier platoon sargent,  and thier medics in the inital motor attack. This left our medic to take care of about a hunderd men.<br>
   Doc did this all night. Running from one side of our posistion to the other. He never ducked, hid , or refused to move even when the Dinks were in the peremeter. He was covered with the blood of others. He checked on everone. <br>
   The next day when we escaped. He made a litter and we carried out the body of one of the line company men that they wanted to leave behind. Doc didn't sleep for three days.<br>
   He was awarded the Silver Star. We worked on a liasion team in a village (Son Hoa} for awhile before we came home. He lives in Minnesota now.<br>
   I knew many medics and I always though that they were the bravest men I ever met. <br>
   There was no one in our platoon that would let any harm come to him or any other other medic if they could stop it.<br>
   Medics were our mothers. They took care of us, shuved pills down our throughts, took care of our sores, watched our diets, and loved us.<br>
   I'm sorry if you didn't feel appreciated then. I think that you were and just didn't know it. Doc the medics of every war were much admired. I belive that they are the most decorated soldiers in history and have more Medals of Honor than any other group of soldiers. And it's a fact that they have the biggest set of BALLS in the military. <br><br>
                         Fez
